Part 1: Data

The General Social Survey (GSS) is a nationally representative survey of adults in the United States conducted since 1972. The GSS collects data on contemporary American society in order to monitor and explain trends in opinions, attitudes and behaviors. The GSS has adapted questions from earlier surveys, thereby allowing researchers to conduct comparisons for up to 80 years. More information can be found on the web site of the GSS project https://gss.norc.org/About-The-GSS

GSS collects data using multi-stage survey design, which needs to be considered in order to generalize to the whole US population. To make my results generalizable Im going to use the survey analysis library https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/survey/index.html

This is observational study so only correlational inference can be made.

This particular dataset is not very good for analyzing numerical data - the study design intended to be categorical based (opinions, attitudes and behaviours trends). So even supposed to be numerical data like respondents income is originally collected as categorical data and then post processed which imply inevitable loss of information. And second - the dataset is not large enough for in-depth (based on many sub-variables) analysis and inference.

Part 2: Research question

Gender pay gap

According to Bureau of Labor Statistics data, in 2020, womens annual earnings were 82.3% of mens, and the gap is even wider formany women of color. Though women only made 57 cents per dollar earned by men in 1973 when this Department of Labor PSA was made, progress has stalled and were still far from closing the pay gap.

Compared with white men with the same education, Black and Latina women with only a bachelors degree have the largest gap at 65%, and Black women with advanced degrees earn 70% of what white men with advanced degrees earn. Educational attainment is not enough to close gender earnings gaps. In fact, most women with advanced degrees earn less than white men, on average, with only a bachelors degree.

Unfortunately, the pandemic stalled gains made toward closing the pay gap, and layoffs and a lack of child care have forced many women out of the workforce entirely. In February 2021, womens labor force participation rate was 55.8% the same rate as April 1987. And women of color and those working in low-wage occupations have been the most impacted.

From https://blog.dol.gov/2021/03/19/5-facts-about-the-state-of-the-gender-pay-gap

I would like to see the general yearly dynamic in the gender pay gap as well as the influence of some other factors such as class, race and age on this dynamic. In my analysis I tried to select variables with the maximum available information across the dataset.

  • conrinc

Inflation-adjusted personal income.

Notes: Income variables (INCOME, RINCOM77, RINCOM82, RINCOM86, RINCOM91) are recoded in six-digit numbers and converted to 2000 dollars. The collapsed numbers above are for convenience of display only. Since this variable is based on categorical data, income is not continuous, but based on categorical mid-points and imputations. For details see GSS Methodological Report No.101.

The data is not available for 2021.

  • sex

The variable SEX in face-to-face interviews, interviewers traditionally coded SEX based on interviewer observation

  • degree

Respondents degree

  • class

If you were asked to use one of four names for your social class, which would you say you belong in: the lower class, the working class, the middle class, or the upper class?

  • race

What race do you consider yourself?

  • age_group

arbitrary derivative from the variable age

Respondents age

Survey design

gss_num_design <-svydesign(id = ~vpsu, 
                           strata = ~vstrat, 
                           data = subset(gss_num, !is.na(conrinc) & year!=2010
                                         & class!="no class"), 
                           weights = ~wtssall, 
                           nest = TRUE)

#removing empty label for class = "no class"
gss_num_design <- update(gss_num_design,class=droplevels(class))

#requred for this particular design
options(survey.lonely.psu="remove")

Im going to create object using srvyr library to use lazy tidyverse syntax whenever I want to

gss_num_srvyr_design <- as_survey(gss_num_design)

There is a noticeable difference in weighted and unweighted distribution. Without accounting for this difference results will be biased and variance calculated incorrectly, which can result in the wrong inference.

For survey.design objects the default is interval.type="Wald". A 95% Wald confidence interval is constructed for the proportion below the estimated quantile. The inverse of the estimated CDF is used to map this to a confidence interval for the quantile.

Part 4: Inference

T-test and ANOVA inference is mean-based. Conditions for both are satisfied:

  • independence - observations are independent between and within the groups, data is not paired (from GSS survey design), sample size <10% of the population

  • distribution of the data within each group is not normal, but sample size is big enough.

  • variability across the groups is about equal

T test

H0: there is no difference between mean income of males and females \(\mu_{male} = \mu_{female}\)

H1: there is a difference between mean income of males and females \(\mu_{male} \neq \mu_{female}\)

##Inference for quantitative data ###Survey-weighted t-test
svyttest(formula = conrinc~sex,
         design = gss_num_design)
## 
##  Design-based t-test
## 
## data:  conrinc ~ sex
## t = -42.789, df = 2079, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -17758.02 -16201.58
## sample estimates:
## difference in mean 
##           -16979.8

ANOVA

For each of the variable we have a pair of hypotheses

H0: there is no difference between mean income \(\mu_{1} = \mu_{2} = \mu_{...} =\mu_{i}\)

H1: there is a difference between mean income \(\mu_{1} \neq \mu_{2} \neq \mu_{...} \neq \mu_{i}\)

To extract ANOVA table from survey design based model I have to use GLM model first.

# Extracting ANOVA table for income by degree and sex
gss.glm1 <- svyglm(conrinc~sex+degree+race+class+age_group, design=gss_num_design)
atable <- anova(gss.glm1)
atable
## Anova table:  (Rao-Scott LRT)

Both variants shows that all variables are significant with p-value approaching zero. Thus we can reject both H0 hypotheses.
